hical Society of South Australia] blog entries for Afghanistan & the British Raj that cover the subject chronologically with images through reference works in our collection.\n\n{{Anglo-Afghan War}}\n{{Afghanistan topics}}\n{{British colonial campaigns}}\n\n[[Category:Second Anglo-Afghan War|01]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Afghan Wars|02]]\n[[Category:1870s in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:1880s in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Emirate of Afghanistan|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Afghanistan|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:Invasions by the United Kingdom|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Afghanistan|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:The Great Game]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Afghanistan|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United Kingdom|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:Battles involving British India|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:Military history of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n[[Category:1878 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:1879 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:1880 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:1870s in British India]]\n[[Category:1880s in British India]]\n[[Category:Battle honours of the King's Royal Rifle Corps]]\n[[Category:19th-century military history of the United Kingdom|Anglo-Afghan War 02]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Second Anglo\u2013Afghan War\n|partof      = [[The Great Game]]\n|image       = Battle in Afghanistan.jpg\n|image_size  = 300px\n|caption     = ''[[92nd (Gordon Highlanders) Regiment of Foot|92nd Highlanders]] at Kandahar''. Oil by [[Richard Caton Woodville Jr.]]\n|date        = 1878\u20131880\n|place       = [[Emirate of Afghanistan]]\n|coordinates =\n|map_type    =\n|latitude    =\n|longitude   =\n|map_size    =\n|map_marksize =\n|map_caption =\n|map_label   =\n|territory   = Districts of [[Quetta District|Quetta]], [[Pishin District|Pishin]], [[Sibi District|Sibi]], [[Harnai District|Harnai]] & Thal Chotiali ceded to [[British India]]<ref name=\"blood1995\">Blood pp. 20-21</ref>\n|result = British Victory<ref>http://www.branchcollective.org/?ps_articles=zarena-aslami-the-second-anglo-afghan-war-or-the-return-of-the-uninvited</ref><ref>https://www.thoughtco.com/britains-second-war-in-afghanistan-1773763</ref><ref>https://www.britannica.com/event/Second-Anglo-Afghan-War</ref>\n\n*[[Treaty of Gandamak]]<ref name=\"Schmidt\">{{cite book |last=Schmidt |first=Karl J. |title=An Atlas and Survey of South Asian History |year=1995 |publisher=M.E. Sharpe |isbn=978-1563243332 |page=[https://archive.org/details/atlassurveyofsou0000schm/page/74 74] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/atlassurveyofsou0000schm/page/74 }}</ref><ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Adamec |first1=L.W. |last2=Norris |first2=J.A. |url=http://iranicaonline.org/articles/anglo-afghan-wars |title=Anglo-Afghan Wars |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]] |date=2010 }}</ref> \n* Afghanistan becomes a [[British Protectorate]]<ref name=\"Barfield146\">Barfield p.146</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Toriya |first1=Masato |title=- 49 - Afghanistan as a Buffer  State between Regional Powers in the Late  Nineteenth Century |url=http://src-h.slav.hokudai.ac.jp/rp/publications/no14/14-05_Toriya.pdf |website=Cross Disciplinary Studies |publisher=Hokkaido University |accessdate=25 November 2018 |page=49}}</ref> \n* British withdrawal from [[Afghanistan]]<ref name=\"Iranica\">{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Adamec |first1=L.W. |last2=Norris |first2=J.A. |url=http://iranicaonline.org/articles/anglo-afghan-wars |title=Anglo-Afghan Wars |work=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]] |date=2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"Barfield146\"/><ref name=\"Posturee\">{{Cite book |title=Understanding Holocausts: How, Why and When They Occur |last1=Posturee |first1=Bad |year=2002 |publisher=iUniverse |isbn=978-0-595-23838-5 |page=84 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6TgXuP-ezB8C&lpg=PR1&pg=PA84 |accessdate=22 August 2010 }}</ref>\n|combatant1  = <p>{{flagcountry|Emirate of Afghanistan|1709}}</p><!-- `p` tag to make vertical alignment match the adjacent cell -->\n|combatant2  = {{flag|British Empire}}\n* {{flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n* {{flagcountry|British Raj}}\n|commander1  = {{Plainlist}}\n* {{flagicon|Emirate of Afghanistan|1709}} [[Sher Ali Khan]]\n* {{flagicon|Emirate of Afghanistan|1709}} [[Ayub Khan (Emir of Afghanistan)|Ayub Khan]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n|commander2  = {{Plainlist}}\n* {{flagicon|British Raj}} [[Sam Browne|Samuel Browne]]\n* {{flagicon|British Raj}} [[Frederick Roberts, 1st Earl Roberts|Frederick Roberts]]\n* {{flagicon|British Raj}} [[Sir Donald Stewart, 1st Baronet|Donald Stewart]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n|strength2   =\n|casualties1 = Total fatalities are unknown \n*5,000+ killed in major battles<ref name=\"Robson\">{{cite book |last=Robson |first=Brian. |title=The Road to Kabul: The Second Afghan War 1878\u20131881 |year=2007 |publisher=Spellmount |location=Stroud |isbn=978-1-86227-416-7 |page=299 }}</ref>\n|casualties2 = Total: 9,850 fatalities\n*1,850 [[killed in action]] or died of wounds\n*8,000 died of diseases<ref name=\"Robson\"/>\n|casualties3 =\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Second Anglo-Afghan War}}\n{{Campaignbox Conflicts in Afghanistan (1823-1973)}}\n{{History of Afghanistan}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Second Anglo-Afghan War''' ({{lang-ps|\u062f \u0627\u0641\u063a\u0627\u0646-\u0627\u0646\u06ab\u0631\u06d0\u0632 \u062f\u0648\u064a\u0645\u0647 \u062c\u06ab\u0693\u0647}}) was a military conflict fought between the [[British Raj]] and the [[Emirate of Afghanistan]] from 1878 to 1880, when the latter was ruled by [[Sher Ali Khan]] of the [[Barakzai dynasty]], the son of former [[Emir]] [[Dost Mohammad Khan (Emir of Afghanistan)|Dost Mohammad Khan]]. The war was part of the [[Great Game]] between the [[British Empire|British]] and [[Russian empire]]s.\n\nThe war was split into two campaigns - the first began in November 1878 with the [[British Raj|British]] invasion of Afghanistan. The British were quickly victorious and forced the [[Amir]] - [[Sher Ali Khan]] to flee. Ali's successor [[Mohammad Yaqub Khan]] immediately sued for peace and the [[Treaty of Gandamak]] was then signed on 26 May 1879. The British sent an envoy and mission led by Sir [[Louis Cavagnari]] to Kabul but on 3 September this mission was massacred and the conflict was reignited by [[Mohammad Ayub Khan (Emir of Afghanistan)|Ayub Khan]] which led to the [[abdication]] of Yaqub.<ref name=\"EB1911\">{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Yakub Khan |volume=28 |page=898}}</ref>\n\nThe second campaign ended in September 1880 when the British [[Battle of Kandahar|decisively defeated]] Ayub Khan outside [[Kandahar]]. A new Amir - [[Abdur Rahman Khan]] selected by the British, ratified and confirmed the Gandamak treaty once more. When the British and Indian soldiers had withdrawn, the Afghans agreed to let the British attain all of their geopolitical objectives, as well as create a buffer between the [[British Raj]] and the Russian Empire.<ref name=\"Barfield145\">Barfield p. 145</ref>\n\n==Background==\nAfter tension between Russia and Britain in Europe ended with the June 1878 [[Congress of Berlin]], Russia turned its attention to Central Asia. That same summer, Russia sent an uninvited diplomatic mission to Kabul. [[Sher Ali Khan]], the [[Amir of Afghanistan]], tried unsuccessfully to keep them out. Russian envoys arrived in Kabul on 22 July 1878, and on 14 August, the British demanded that Sher Ali accept a British mission too.<ref name=Barthorp66_67>{{cite book |last=Barthorp |first=Michael |title=Afghan Wars and the North-West Frontier 1839\u20131947|origyear=1982 |year=2002 |publisher=Cassell |location=London |isbn=0-304-36294-8 |pages=66\u201367}}</ref>\n\nThe Amir not only refused to receive a British mission under [[Neville Bowles Chamberlain]], but threatened to stop it if it were dispatched. [[Robert Bulwer-Lytton, 1st Earl of Lytton|Lord Lytton]], the [[viceroy of India]], ordered a diplomatic mission to set out for Kabul in September 1878 but the mission was turned back as it approached the eastern entrance of the [[Khyber Pass]], triggering the Second Anglo\u2013Afghan War.<ref name=Barthorp66_67/>\n\n==War==\n===First phase===\nThe first campaign began in November 1878 when a British force of about 50,000 fighting men, mostly Indians, was distributed into three military columns which penetrated Afghanistan at three different points. The British victories at the [[Battle of Ali Masjid]] and the [[Battle of Peiwar Kotal]] meant that the approach to Kabul was left virtually undefended by Afghan troops.<ref>[http://www.britishempire.co.uk/forces/armycampaigns/indiancampaigns/campafghan1878.htm Afghanistan 1878-1880 The Build-Up to Conflict] at britishempire.co.uk</ref>\n\nAn alarmed [[Sher Ali Khan|Sher Ali]] attempted to appeal in person to the Russian Tsar for assistance, but their insistence was that he should seek terms of surrender from the British.<ref>Sinhai, Damodar Prasad. \"India and Afghanistan, 1876\", p. 183.</ref> He returned to [[Mazar-i-Sharif]], where he died on 21 February 1879.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Hanna|first=Henry Bathurst|title=The Second Afghan War, 1878-79-80: Its Causes, Its Conduct and Its Consequences|publisher=Archibald Constable & Co|year=1904|volume=2|pages=150\u2013155|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GzQoAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Treaty===\nWith British forces occupying much of the country, Sher Ali's son and successor, [[Mohammad Yaqub Khan]], signed the [[Treaty of Gandamak]] in May 1879 to prevent a British invasion of the rest of the country. According to this agreement and in return for an annual subsidy and vague assurances of assistance in case of foreign aggression, Yaqub relinquished control of Afghan foreign affairs to Britain. British representatives were installed in Kabul and other locations, British control was extended to the [[Khyber Pass|Khyber]] and [[Michni Pass|Michni]] passes, and Afghanistan ceded various [[North-West Frontier Province (1901\u201355)|North-West Frontier Province]] [[Federally Administered Tribal Areas (FATA)|areas]] and [[Quetta]] to Britain. The British Army then withdrew.<ref>{{cite book |last=Barthorp |first=Michael |title=Afghan Wars and the North-West Frontier 1839\u20131947|origyear=1982 |year=2002 |publisher=Cassell |location=London |isbn=0-304-36294-8 |pages=71}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on 3 September 1879 an uprising in Kabul led to the slaughter of [[Pierre Louis Napoleon Cavagnari|Sir Louis Cavagnari]], the British representative, along with his guards, and staff \u2013 provoking the next phase of the Second Afghan War.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilkinson-Latham |first=Robert |origyear=1977 |year=1998|title=North-West Frontier 1837\u20131947 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=London |isbn=0-85045-275-9 |page=15}}</ref>\n\n===Second phase===\n[[File:Elephant and Mule Battery (\"Dignity & Impudence\") WDL11496.png|thumb|Titled \"Dignity & Impudence\" for [[stereotype|stereotypic]] [[personality trait]]s of elephants and mules respectively, this photograph by [[John Burke (photographer)|John Burke]] shows an elephant and mule battery during the Second Anglo-Afghan War. The mule team would have hauled supplies or towed the small [[field gun]], while the elephants towed the larger gun. The gun appears to be a [[Rifled Muzzle Loader]] (RML) 7-pounder mountain gun. The men in the photograph are a mix of British soldiers and Indian [[sepoy]]s. The group kneeling around the smaller, [[muzzle-load]]ed field gun is preparing to fire after the soldier at front left has used the [[ramrod]] to push the charge down into the gun. The gun at right, towed by elephants, appears to be a [[Rifled breech loader]] (RBL) 40-pounder Armstrong]]\n\nMajor General Sir [[Frederick Roberts, 1st Earl Roberts|Frederick Roberts]] led the [[Kabul Field Force]] over the Shutargardan Pass into central Afghanistan, defeated the [[Afghan Army]] at [[Battle of Charasiab|Charasiab]] on 6 October 1879, and occupied [[Kabul]] two days later.<ref>{{cite book |last=Barthorp |first=Michael |title=Afghan Wars and the North-West Frontier 1839\u20131947|origyear=1982 |year=2002 |publisher=Cassell |location=London |isbn=0-304-36294-8 |pages=77\u201379}}</ref> [[Ghazi warriors|Ghazi]] [[Mohammad Jan Khan Wardak]], and a force of 10,000 Afghans, staged an uprising and attacked British forces near Kabul in the [[Siege of the Sherpur Cantonment]] in December 1879. Despite besieging the British garrison there, he failed to maintain the Siege of Sherpur, instead shifting focus to Roberts' force, and this resulted in the collapse of this rebellion. Yaqub Khan, suspected of complicity in the massacre of Cavagnari and his staff, was obliged to abdicate. The British considered a number of possible political settlements, including partitioning Afghanistan between multiple rulers or placing Yaqub's brother [[Mohammad Ayub Khan (Emir of Afghanistan)|Ayub Khan]] on the throne, but ultimately decided to install his cousin [[Abdur Rahman Khan]] as emir instead.<ref name=Wilkinson16_17>{{cite book |last=Wilkinson-Latham |first=Robert |origyear=1977 |year=1998|title=North-West Frontier 1837\u20131947 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |location=London |isbn=0-85045-275-9 |pages=16\u201317}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Barthorp |first=Michael |title=Afghan Wars and the North-West Frontier 1839\u20131947|origyear=1982 |year=2002 |publisher=Cassell |location=London |isbn=0-304-36294-8 |pages=81\u201385}}</ref>\n[[File:Coin minted in Kandahar during its occupation during the Second Anglo-Afghan War.jpg|thumb|A rare coin minted during the occupation of Kandahar. British Crown within [[wreath]] on the obverse, Arabic inscription in four lines on the reverse. These issues were struck under local authorities who routinely recalled and devalued the coppers. This abusive practice lead to a great variety of types, often featuring various animal or flower motifs. Accordingly, the types on this coin were likely not ordered by the occupation authorities, but rather placed by an opportunistic engraver eager to please the occupiers.]]\nAyub Khan, who had been serving as governor of Herat, rose in revolt, defeated a British detachment at the [[Battle of Maiwand]] in July 1880 and besieged Kandahar. Roberts then led the main British force from Kabul and decisively defeated Ayub Khan on 1 September at the [[Battle of Kandahar]], bringing his rebellion to an end.<ref name=Wilkinson16_17/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nWith Ayub Khan defeated, the war was officially over and the British selected and supported a new Amir - [[Abdur Rahman Khan]] son of [[Muhammad Afzal]] and nephew of the former Amir Sher Ali. Rahman confirmed the Treaty of Gandamak, whereby the British took control of the territories ceded by Yaqub Khan, and also of Afghanistan's [[foreign relations of Afghanistan|foreign policy]] in exchange for protection and a subsidy.<ref>{{cite book |last=Barthorp |first=Michael |title=Afghan Wars and the North-West Frontier 1839\u20131947|origyear=1982 |year=2002 |publisher=Cassell |location=London |isbn=0-304-36294-8 |pages=85\u201390}}</ref> The [[Pashtun tribes|Afghan tribes]] maintained internal rule and local customs, and provided a continuing buffer between the [[British Raj]] and the [[Russian Empire]].<ref name=\"Barfield145\"/>\n\nAbandoning the provocative policy of maintaining a British resident in Kabul, but having achieved all their other objectives, the British withdrew from the region.<ref name=Wilkinson16_17/> By April 1881 all British and Indian troops had left Afghanistan, but British Indian agents were left behind to smooth liaison between the governments.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Prasad |first1=Bisheshwar |title=Foundations of India's Foreign Policy: Imperial Era, 1882-1914 |date=1979 |publisher=Nayad Prokash |page=25 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GIQcAAAAMAAJ&q=}}</ref> No further trouble resulted between Afghanistan and British India during Rahman's period of rule, and he became known as the 'iron Amir'. The Russians kept well out of Afghan internal affairs, with the exception of the [[Panjdeh incident]] three years later, resolved by arbitration and negotiation after an initial British ultimatum.<ref>[https://books.google.com.au/books?id=bv4hzxpo424C&pg=PA198 ''Conflict in Afghanistan: A Historical Encyclopedia''] By Clements, F. ABC-Clio, Santa Barbara, California, 2003 p. 198</ref>\n\nIn 1893, [[Mortimer Durand]] was despatched to Kabul by British India to sign an agreement with Rahman for fixing the limits of their respective [[spheres of influence]] as well as improving diplomatic relations and trade. On November 12, 1893, the [[Durand Line]] Agreement was reached. leading to the creation of a new [[North-West Frontier Province (1901\u20131955)|North-West Frontier Province]].\n\n==Timeline of battles==\nThere were several decisive actions in the Second Anglo\u2013Afghan War, from 1878 to 1880. Here are the battles and actions in chronological order. An asterisk (*) indicates a [[Medal bar|clasp]] was awarded for that particular battle with the [[Afghanistan Medal (United Kingdom)|Afghanistan Medal]].\n\n[[File:Battle of Ali Masjid - 19 members of the Yorkshire Infantry.jpg|thumb|British team at the site of the [[Battle of Ali Masjid]]]]\n[[File:Royal Horse Artillery fleeing from Afghan attack at the Battle of Maiwand.jpg|thumb|British [[Royal Horse Artillery]] withdrawing at the [[Battle of Maiwand]]]]\n[[File:Victory day at Kandahar 1880.jpg|thumb|Afghan victors of the Battle of Maiwand]]\n\n===1878===\n# [[Battle of Ali Masjid]]* (British victory)\n# [[Battle of Peiwar Kotal]]* (British victory)\n\n===1879===\n# Action at Takht-i-Pul (British victory)\n# Action at Matun (British victory)\n# Battle of Khushk-i-Nakud (British victory)\n# Battle of Fatehabad (Afghan victory)\n# Battle of Kam Dakka (Afghan victory)\n# Battle of Charasiab* (British victory)<ref name=Alikuzai>{{cite book|last=Alikuzai|first=Hamid Wahed|title=A Concise History of Afghanistan in 25 Volumes, Volume 14|year=2013|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=1490714413|page=594}}</ref> \n# Battle of Shajui\n# Battle of Karez Mir\n# Battle of Takht-i-Shah\n# Battle of Asmai Heights* (Afghan victory)\n# [[Siege of Sherpur]]* (British victory)\n\n===1880===\n# [[Battle of Ahmed Khel]]* (British victory)\n# Battle of Arzu\n# [[Second Battle of Charasiab]]\n# [[Battle of Maiwand]] (Afghan victory)\n# Battle of Deh Koja (Afghan Victory)\n# [[Battle of Kandahar]]* (British victory)\n\n===1881===\n# Kandahar (and Afghanistan) Evacuation\n\n==Order of battle==\n{{unreferenced section|date=August 2016}}\n[[File:Durbar Maidan of Sherpur Cantonment in 1879.jpg|thumb|Durban Maidan of Sherpur Cantonment in 1879.]]\n[[File:Bengal Sapper and Miners Bastion, in Sherpur cantonment, Kabul, Second Afghan War, c. 1879.jpg|thumb|Bengal Sapper and Miners Bastion in Sherpur cantonment.]]\n[[File:Highlanders of Amir Yaqub at Gandamak.jpg|thumb|Highlanders of Amir Yaqub at [[Gandamak]]]]\n[[File:William Skeoch Cumming01.jpg|thumb|Drummer James Roddick of the [[92nd (Gordon Highlanders) Regiment of Foot|Gordon Highlanders]] defends a wounded officer during British attack at Gundi Mulla Sahibdad during the [[Battle of Kandahar]]]]\n[[File:45th Sikh Regiment escorting prisoners - 2nd afghan war.jpg|thumb|[[45th Rattray's Sikhs]] guard Afghan prisoners during an advance through the [[Khyber Pass]]]]\n* [[Peshawar Valley]] Field Force Lieutenant General [[Sam Browne|Sir Samuel Browne]]\n** Cavalry Brigade Brigadier General [[Charles John Stanley Gough|C. J. S. Gough]]\n*** [[10th Hussars]] (2 Sqdns)\n*** [[11th Probyn's Lancers]]\n*** [[Guides Cavalry]]\n** Royal Artillery\n** First Infantry Brigade Brigadier General [[Herbert Taylor MacPherson|H. T. Macpherson]]\n*** 4th Battalion [[Rifle Brigade]]\n*** [[20th Duke of Cambridge's Own Infantry (Brownlow's Punjabis)|20th Brownlow's Punjabis]]\n*** [[4th Gurkha Rifles]